      Elsewhere in meme-stock investing
   =20
 =20
The Wall Street Journal has an article about =E2=80=9CThe Social-Media Star=
s Who Move Markets=E2=80=9D and oh man is it something:=E2=80=9CTraditional=
 finance is a black box,=E2=80=9D said Sarah Petite, a social-media consult=
ant in Los Angeles. =E2=80=9CThis generation is looking at their parents an=
d saying, =E2=80=98The way you thought about money? That isn=E2=80=99t how =
it works anymore.=E2=80=99 =E2=80=9DInstead, young people want a road map t=
o how to make big profits, and a strong independent streak draws many of th=
em to online influencers who dole out advice free, rather than paying a tra=
ditional investment manager to handle their money for them. Many don=E2=80=
=99t care much about the qualifications of who=E2=80=99s giving the advice,=
 experts and young investors themselves say.=E2=80=9CI have a rule: Don=E2=
=80=99t pay for something you can get free,=E2=80=9D said Rex Wu, a 33-year=
-old investor from Tampa Bay, Fla., who is a regular viewer of [YouTube sto=
ck-market influencer and also somehow California gubernatorial candidate Ke=
vin] Paffrath and several other online finance-world personalities. He says=
 he has invested a few hundred thousand dollars based on =E2=80=9Cthings I=
=E2=80=99ve learned online from guys like Kevin.=E2=80=9D So far this year,=
 his portfolio has returned 23%; year-to-date, the S&P 500 has returned 21%=
.=E2=80=9CIf I were to walk into JPMorgan tomorrow, they have the bias of t=
rying to earn my business, and they might be trying to oversell me,=E2=80=
=9D Mr. Wu said. =E2=80=9CGuys online don=E2=80=99t really have anything th=
ey=E2=80=99re trying to sell me.=E2=80=9DOkay so between =E2=80=9Cdon=E2=80=
=99t pay for something you can get free=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Cdon=E2=80=99t=
 get something free that you could pay for,=E2=80=9D I think the latter mig=
ht be better advice? I mean neither is a hard-and-fast rule or anything but=
 in the long run there is some truth to the idea that you get what you pay =
for? Also=C2=A0guys online definitely have things they=E2=80=99re trying to=
 sell you?=C2=A0Like most internet content, influencer videos thrive on pop=
ularity. And in the midst of a long-running bull market, what=E2=80=99s pop=
ular is success stories and hot tips only.Many influencers report that when=
 they hype an investment, they get the page views they crave. When the mess=
age is bearish, however, viewers turn away, or worse, attack the messenger =
with vicious trolling. =E2=80=A6Most [of Kevin Paffrath=E2=80=99s] videos w=
ith positive titles garner more than 200,000 views, he says, while videos t=
hat have negative takes on a company or an industry in the title rarely get=
 more than 60,000 views.=E2=80=9CI have to be an astronaut and show them th=
at the rocket ship is fun, but you can=E2=80=99t look at that your whole li=
fe,=E2=80=9D Mr. Paffrath said.=E2=80=9CI=E2=80=99ll play the momentum game=
, but let=E2=80=99s be real: True wealth comes from long-run interest. The =
trouble is, on YouTube, none of my videos about that kind of thing get any =
views.=E2=80=9DLook, the thing about =E2=80=9Ctraditional finance is a blac=
k box=E2=80=9D is that it actually comes with a fairly complete and well-un=
derstood=C2=A0explanatory structure. =E2=80=9CWhy is this stock worth $X? B=
ecause the present value of its expected future cash flows is $X. What does=
 that mean? Well, here=E2=80=99s the Wikipedia page on discounted cash flow=
 modeling, and here are six analyst reports projecting the company=E2=80=99=
s future cash flows, which are based on guidance from the company, and here=
 is a spreadsheet with all of my inputs and assumptions.=E2=80=9D Like it i=
s a =E2=80=9Cblack box=E2=80=9D in the sense that, if you don=E2=80=99t wan=
t to bother with learning all of that stuff, you won=E2=80=99t understand i=
t, but that is true of most things. And it is a =E2=80=9Cblack box=E2=80=9D=
 in the related sense that there are professionals who will worry about it =
for you, so you don=E2=80=99t have to=C2=A0bother with learning all of that=
 stuff. Also right yes of course that explanatory structure does not work=
=C2=A0especially=C2=A0well; stocks are regularly over- or under-valued comp=
ared to their actual future cash flows, and move around too much to be just=
ified by changes in those expectations, and those professionals have a hard=
 time beating the market. Still it is =E2=80=A6=C2=A0there is a way to thin=
k about it, you know?=C2=A0And then meme investing in 2021 is like =E2=80=
=9CI have to be an astronaut and show them that the rocket ship is fun=E2=
=80=9D and yes right in a sense all of this stuff is=C2=A0simple=C2=A0=E2=
=80=94=C2=A0=E2=80=9Clet=E2=80=99s all buy the same stock and then it will =
go up=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94 but =E2=80=A6=C2=A0is it not a =E2=80=9Cblack box=
=E2=80=9D? Is it not totally resistant to understanding and analysis and ex=
planation and meaning? Is it not just =E2=80=9Cthis stock is going to $10,0=
00 because that=E2=80=99s a very large number that is fun to say=E2=80=9D? =
How did you calculate that number?=C2=A0Or am I just old? Anyway I don=E2=
=80=99t know what to tell you but I guess a lot of people on YouTube do.
