      Are SPACs investment companies?
   =20
 =20
No, say all the law firms that work with special purpose investment compani=
es:When 49 major national law firms banded together late last week to=C2=A0=
condemn lawsuits targeting special purpose acquisition companies, the deal-=
making world took notice. =E2=80=A6SPACs have recently come under attack in=
 high-profile shareholder suits that challenge their fundamental structure,=
 starting with an action against the $4 billion blank-check firm run by the=
 billionaire investor Bill Ackman, which forced him to rethink his approach=
. =E2=80=A6=C2=A0Two prominent securities law professors, John Morley of Ya=
le and the former S.E.C. commissioner Robert Jackson, now of Columbia, were=
 behind the suits.=C2=A0Kirkland & Ellis, one of the top legal advisers to =
SPACs, helped to organize other firms to issue the statement, which said th=
e lawsuits are =E2=80=9Cwithout factual or legal basis.=E2=80=9D Some who s=
igned on, like Simpson Thacher & Bartlett, have comparatively little involv=
ement with SPACs. They are protesting on principle, organizers said. =E2=80=
=9CThe market has already driven some reform,=E2=80=9D said Christian Nagle=
r of Kirkland & Ellis. =E2=80=9COtherwise it should be done by proposing ru=
les and laws, not by lawsuits.=E2=80=9DWe talked about this  last week: Som=
e law professors are suing some SPACs, claiming that they are =E2=80=9Cinve=
stment companies=E2=80=9D under the=C2=A0Investment Company Act of 1940 and=
 therefore, essentially, illegal. (Or at least, it's illegal for their spon=
sors to get all the fees that they get.) I think those professors are wrong=
, and all these law firms agree with me. Of course the law firms are biased=
: If SPACs are in fact illegal, then the law firms can't charge any more fe=
es for raising SPACs. I suppose they can charge some fees for unwinding the=
m, I dunno. Still I think the law firms are right.One raw fact here is that=
 there are a lot of SPACs, and they=E2=80=99ve been around for a while, and=
 nobody has really said this before. None of their law firms have told them=
 =E2=80=9Chey you are an investment company under the =E2=80=9940 Act,=E2=
=80=9D and the U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission, which has reviewed =
all of the SPACs=E2=80=99 filings, has not told any of them =E2=80=9Chey yo=
u=E2=80=99re an investment company and can=E2=80=99t charge all these fees.=
=E2=80=9D=C2=A0In general, if you see that fact, and you don=E2=80=99t both=
er to read a word of the =E2=80=9940 Act, you could reasonably conclude =E2=
=80=9Cwell that means SPACs are not investment companies.=E2=80=9D Surely i=
f they were investment companies under the=C2=A0=E2=80=9940 Act, someone wo=
uld have noticed by now.There is just sort of an efficient-markets-ish argu=
ment: A lot of smart people (deal lawyers, plaintiffs=E2=80=99 lawyers, the=
 SEC)=C2=A0have a lot of good incentives to read the =E2=80=9940 Act, all t=
he way through, and notice if a big sector of the market is violating it. T=
he fact that no one has noticed that over many years=C2=A0probably=C2=A0mea=
ns that there=E2=80=99s nothing to notice. Of course the fact that two smar=
t law professors did notice it this year, or say they did anyway,=C2=A0is c=
ontrary evidence, but not much.=C2=A0And if they were=C2=A0arguably investm=
ent companies under the=C2=A0=E2=80=9940 Act, but the SEC over the course o=
f many years consistently treated them as not investment companies, then th=
at is itself a regulatory decision that is entitled to some precedential we=
ight.[2] If there is doubt about whether SPACs are=C2=A0=E2=80=9940 Act inv=
estment companies, the SEC=E2=80=99s consistent treatment of them as=C2=A0n=
ot investment companies should really settle the issue.
 =20
