      Another look at last look
   =20
 =20
We  talked on Thursday about =E2=80=9Clast look,=E2=80=9D the practice in t=
he foreign exchange market in which dealers sometimes walk away from trades=
 if the price moves against them. I was like, yes, right, of course a deale=
r would do that, if it could. I also noted that of course a dealer would ba=
ck out of a trade if the price moved=C2=A0against=C2=A0it, but would not fe=
el a similar desire to back out of a trade if the price moved=C2=A0in its f=
avor. There is nothing in =E2=80=9Cthe rules=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=A0more a=
 set of voluntary principles =E2=80=94=C2=A0requiring last look to be used =
symmetrically.That said, I am perhaps too cynical about last look.[3] Sever=
al readers emailed me examples of dealers who promise to use last look symm=
etrically, that is, to have some price-movement threshold and back out of t=
rades if the price moves that amount=C2=A0either way. (For instance, here i=
s JPMorgan Chase & Co.=E2=80=99s last look policy, which says that its =E2=
=80=9CPrice Movement Thresholds are symmetrical =E2=80=93 this means that t=
he same client-specific tolerance level applies to price differences in eit=
her direction.=E2=80=9D) So if you do a trade to buy pounds from a dealer, =
and the pound moves=C2=A0down (against you)=C2=A0in the brief last-look win=
dow, you won=E2=80=99t get filled at the now-stale price either. It=E2=80=
=99s only fair!
