<table class=3D"header" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" cellp=
adding=3D"0">
<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">ESG accounting</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A simple story is that investors want =
to buy stocks and bonds from good companies, companies in strong financial =
positions, companies with high revenues and low expenses and lots of valuab=
le assets. The way to tell that a company has high revenues and low expense=
s and valuable assets is by looking at its financial statements, which help=
fully=C2=A0list its revenues and expenses and assets and liabilities. Obvio=
usly unscrupulous people might start companies and=C2=A0<em>lie=C2=A0</em>o=
n those financial statements, because then they could raise a lot of money =
and keep it for themselves. Or they might not <em>lie=C2=A0</em>exactly, bu=
t instead use odd accounting choices to make their financial position look =
better than it is. So there is a whole profession of auditing, which is bas=
ically in the business of examining companies=E2=80=99 financial statements=
,=C2=A0making sure that they conform to generally accepted accounting princ=
iples and=C2=A0certifying to the investing public that they are more or les=
s true. Sometimes auditors get this wrong, but generally investors trust au=
ditors enough that (1) financial statements audited by reputable accounting=
 firms, particularly the =E2=80=9CBig Four,=E2=80=9D are generally consider=
ed to be more or less true and (2) financial statements that aren=E2=80=99t=
 audited are often viewed with some suspicion.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px =
0;">Traditionally the main thing investors were assumed to want, from a com=
pany, was a strong financial position, so the audited financial statements =
mattered a lot. But of course investors want other things. One thing they w=
ant is strong growth prospects, which is not really something that is refle=
cted in audited historical financial statements; audited financials matter =
a lot less to hot startups looking to raise venture capital than they do to=
 mature industrial companies looking to sell bonds. Another thing they want=
 is just, you know, meme-y stuff. You don=E2=80=99t need an auditor to tell=
 you if a company=E2=80=99s chief executive officer is fun on Twitter.=C2=
=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">These days investors also care a lot ab=
out environmental, social and governance factors. These things are not part=
icularly reflected in financial statements. But they could be! Or, I mean, =
they could be reflected in other statements. ESG statements, I guess. The t=
hing about ESG is that it has some of the same issues that require auditing=
 of financial statements.</p><ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding=
-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Investor=
s want companies with good ESG positions, companies that don=E2=80=99t poll=
ute a lot and treat employees well and so forth.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin=
-bottom: 5px;">Unscrupulous people might lie about how much they pollute, e=
tc.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Or they might just use differe=
nt methods of accounting for their pollution, etc., to make their own perfo=
rmance look good.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">It would be nice=
 to standardize how companies report ESG data, and to have some authority f=
igure to check it and vouch for it.</li></ol><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">E=
SG stuff largely seems factual, measurable, reportable, but the measurement=
 and reporting are not yet standardized in the way that financial reporting=
 is. That creates an opportunity for people who are in the business of stan=
dardizing and certifying=C2=A0corporate measurements and reports. Here is a=
 <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24898515.251678/a=
HR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZnQuY29tL2NvbnRlbnQvNGE0N2ZiNGEtNGExMC00YzA1LThjNWQtMDJkODMw=
NTJiZWU3/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBb8afcaaf" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscop=
e=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; =
border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style=
: solid; background-color: #ccc;">fun Financial Times article</a> about the=
 opportunity:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Now the Big Four =
accounting firms are jumping on a bandwagon that offers two tempting opport=
unities: an expansion of what companies must account for, and a chance to r=
ebrand a scandal-plagued profession as experts on climate change, diversity=
 and winning consumers=E2=80=99 trust. ...</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=
The Big Four are responding in part to a rise in clients=E2=80=99 budgets f=
or developing net zero emissions plans and other sustainability initiatives=
. Tracking nonfinancial metrics such as companies=E2=80=99 carbon footprint=
s, and not simply their financial results, gives them a chance to generate =
more fee income and improve profit margins.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"=
>The introduction of standardised ESG reporting metrics for companies would=
 also create more work for accountants. This will potentially be facilitate=
d by the proposed International Sustainability Standards Board, a body that=
 could be created by November to mirror the role the International Accounti=
ng Standards Board plays in setting financial reporting standards.</p></blo=
ckquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It is not every day that the accountin=
g profession gets a whole new category of thing to account for. Like if you=
 are an accountant right now you pretty much audit the balance sheet and th=
e income statement and the cash flow statement, and if you were an accounta=
nt 50 years ago you pretty much audited those same three statements. But in=
 10 years it is not implausible that accountants will be auditing those thr=
ee statements plus the statement of carbon emissions and the statement of w=
orkplace diversity and who even knows what else. There could be, like, twic=
e as much accounting as there is now! Assuming that they seize the opportun=
ity right away and get everyone to think =E2=80=9Cwe need to reduce our car=
bon emissions, better hire an accountant.=E2=80=9D</p><table class=3D"heade=
r" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" cellpadding=3D"0">
