5px;">Gamification</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here is a U.S. Securities and Exchange=
 Commission <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/248985=
15.251678/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9uZXdzL3ByZXNzLXJlbGVhc2UvMjAyMS0xNjc/6=
07f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB4878103c" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"items=
cope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bot=
tom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; b=
ackground-color: #ccc;">press release</a> with the weirdly enormous title =
=E2=80=9CSEC Requests Information and Comment on Broker-Dealer and Investme=
nt Adviser Digital Engagement Practices, Related Tools and Methods, and Reg=
ulatory Considerations and Potential Approaches; Information and Comments o=
n Investment Adviser Use of Technology.=E2=80=9D Basically the question is,=
 like, =E2=80=9Cis it bad that Robinhood is fun?=E2=80=9D</p><blockquote><p=
 style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The Securities and Exchange Commission today ann=
ounced that it is requesting information and public comment on matters rela=
ted to the use of digital engagement practices by broker-dealers and invest=
ment advisers. These tools include behavioral prompts, differential marketi=
ng, game-like features (commonly referred to as gamification), and other de=
sign elements or features designed to engage with retail investors on digit=
al platforms (e.g., websites, portals, and applications), as well as the an=
alytical and technological tools and methods (collectively called digital e=
ngagement practices (DEPs)).</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">"While new tec=
hnologies can bring us greater access and product choice, they also raise q=
uestions as to whether we as investors are appropriately protected when we =
trade and get financial advice," said SEC Chair Gary Gensler. "In many case=
s, these features may encourage investors to trade more often, invest in di=
fferent products, or change their investment strategy. Predictive analytics=
 and other DEPs often are designed with an optimization function to increas=
e revenues, data collection, or customer time spent on the platform. This m=
ay lead to conflicts between the platform and investors. I=E2=80=99m intere=
sted in the varied questions included in the Request for Comment, and I=E2=
=80=99m particularly focused on how we protect investors engaging with tech=
nologies that use DEPs."</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I hav=
e to say that I sort of sympathize with the SEC=E2=80=99s suspicion that it=
 is bad that Robinhood is fun, but I also sympathize with Robinhood=E2=80=
=99s position that, like, what else are they going to do? They looked at a =
world where the user experience for individual investors was not particular=
ly good, and they were like =E2=80=9Cwhat if we built a retail investing pr=
oduct with a good user experience?=E2=80=9D And that=C2=A0worked, and so pe=
ople used their product a lot. And there was a big backlash as everyone=C2=
=A0was like =E2=80=9Cwait actually it=E2=80=99s bad for a retail investing =
product to have a good user experience, because it is bad for retail invest=
ors to trade too much.=E2=80=9D</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And that ba=
cklash was probably not wrong! Maybe a little too paternalistic, but not=C2=
=A0wrong; compulsive gambling <em>is=C2=A0</em>probably a bad idea.=C2=A0Bu=
t, yeah, I mean, what was Robinhood supposed to do? Intentionally build a b=
ad user experience so people wouldn=E2=80=99t use its product too much?</p>=
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">My first thought here was like =E2=80=9Cit is =
weird to regulate a product for being too user-friendly,=E2=80=9D but is it=
? That is how casinos are regulated, and, like, vape pens. There is an elem=
ent of this sort of thing =E2=80=94=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cyou can sell it, but don=
=E2=80=99t make it too attractive=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=A0in the regulation=
 of alcohol and tobacco and cannabis and pharmaceuticals. It=E2=80=99s how =
people talk about the addictive properties of social media, and sugary drin=
ks and snacks.=C2=A0It is possible that in a society of abundance the basic=
 regulatory problem is that companies will get too good at turning their cu=
stomers into addicts. Maybe regulating Robinhood for being too engaging=C2=
=A0<em>isn=E2=80=99t=C2=A0</em>actually that weird, in 2021.</p><p style=3D=
"margin: 16px 0;">Anyway here is a selection of <a href=3D"https://link.mai=
l.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24898515.251678/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9yd=
Wxlcy9vdGhlci8yMDIxLzM0LTkyNzY2LnBkZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB78e23a1d" it=
emprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-=
decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color:=
 #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">the SEC=E2=
=80=99s questions</a> about =E2=80=9Cdigital engagement practices=E2=80=9D:=
</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">What market forces are driving=
 the adoption of DEPs on digital platforms and how? For example, to what ex=
tent and how is the use of DEPs influenced or driven by=C2=A0market practic=
es related to compensation and revenue (e.g., =E2=80=9Czero commission=E2=
=80=9D and PFOF)? What types of compensation and revenue arrangements influ=
ence or drive market practices related to the use of DEPs? =E2=80=A6</p><p =
style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Do firms use DEPs to promote or otherwise direct =
retail investors to securities, investment strategies, or services that are=
 more lucrative for the firm or that may be riskier to the retail investor =
than others =E2=80=93 such as: margin services, options trading, proprietar=
y products, products for which the firm receives revenue sharing or other t=
hird-party payments, or other higher fee products?=C2=A0 ...</p><p style=3D=
"margin: 16px 0;">Do firms use DEPs to encourage longer-term investment act=
ivities, including, but not limited to, increased contributions to or estab=
lishment of retirement accounts? If so, how? =E2=80=A6</p><p style=3D"margi=
n: 16px 0;">To what extent, and how, do firms use (or in the future expect =
to use) tools based on AI/ML (including deep learning, supervised learning,=
 unsupervised learning, and=C2=A0reinforcement learning) and NLP and NLG, t=
o develop and evolve DEPs? What are the objective functions of AI/ML models=
 (e.g. revenue generation)?</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">To what extent,=
 and how, do firms use (or in the future expect to use) behavioral psycholo=
gy to develop and evolve platforms or DEPs? To what extent, and how, do fir=
ms use (or in the future expect to use) predictive data analytics to develo=
p and evolve DEPs? To what extent, and how, do firms use =E2=80=9Cdark patt=
erns=E2=80=9D in connection with DEPs?</p></blockquote><table class=3D"head=
er" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" cellpadding=3D"0">
