; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-sty=
le: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> last week</a>: Some law professors are=
 suing some SPACs, claiming that they are =E2=80=9Cinvestment companies=E2=
=80=9D under the=C2=A0Investment Company Act of 1940 and therefore, essenti=
ally, illegal. (Or at least, it's illegal for their sponsors to get all the=
 fees that they get.) I think those professors are wrong, and all these law=
 firms <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24898515.25=
1678/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc3RibGF3LmNvbS9kb2NzL2RlZmF1bHQtc291cmNlL3B1YmxpY2F0aW=
9ucy8wOF8yN18yMV9zdGF0ZW1lbnQucGRm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB129981cb" itemp=
rop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-dec=
oration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #0=
00000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">agree with me</=
a>. Of course the law firms are biased: If SPACs are in fact illegal, then =
the law firms can't charge any more fees for raising SPACs. I suppose they =
can charge some fees for unwinding them, I dunno. Still I think the law fir=
ms are right.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One raw fact here is that the=
re are a lot of SPACs, and they=E2=80=99ve been around for a while, and nob=
ody has really said this before. None of their law firms have told them =E2=
=80=9Chey you are an investment company under the =E2=80=9940 Act,=E2=80=9D=
 and the U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission, which has reviewed all of=
 the SPACs=E2=80=99 filings, has not told any of them =E2=80=9Chey you=E2=
=80=99re an investment company and can=E2=80=99t charge all these fees.=E2=
=80=9D=C2=A0<em>In general</em>, if you see that fact, and you don=E2=80=99=
t bother to read a word of the =E2=80=9940 Act, you could reasonably conclu=
de =E2=80=9Cwell that means SPACs are not investment companies.=E2=80=9D Su=
rely if they were investment companies under the=C2=A0=E2=80=9940 Act, some=
one would have noticed by now.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There is jus=
t sort of an efficient-markets-ish argument: A lot of smart people (deal la=
wyers, plaintiffs=E2=80=99 lawyers, the SEC)=C2=A0have a lot of good incent=
ives to read the =E2=80=9940 Act, all the way through, and notice if a big =
sector of the market is violating it. The fact that no one has noticed that=
 over many years=C2=A0<em>probably=C2=A0</em>means that there=E2=80=99s not=
hing to notice. Of course the fact that two smart law professors did notice=
 it this year, or say they did anyway,=C2=A0is contrary evidence, but not m=
uch.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And if they were=C2=A0<em>arguab=
ly</em> investment companies under the=C2=A0=E2=80=9940 Act, but the SEC ov=
er the course of many years consistently treated them as not investment com=
panies, then that is itself a regulatory decision that is entitled to some =
precedential weight.[2] If there is doubt about whether SPACs are=C2=A0=E2=
=80=9940 Act investment companies, the SEC=E2=80=99s consistent treatment o=
f them as=C2=A0<em>not</em> investment companies should really settle the i=
ssue.</p><table class=3D"header" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D=
